{"_id":"a54ac280-468b-11ea-8709-e79a8cf0fe62","postId":"2013_04_implicit-async-context-asynclocal-f13467e9-235a-3d80-9d73-143a2fd30bb5","postUri":"https://blog.stephencleary.com/2013/04/implicit-async-context-asynclocal.html","replyTo":"ae711200-4682-11ea-8709-e79a8cf0fe62","authorEmailEncrypted":"","authorEmailMD5":"23448e78d187fba56d8bc263081ac5d8","authorName":"Stephen Cleary","authorUri":"https://stephencleary.com","message":"> for different incoming requests - it still should run in different `ExecutionContext`s. Is that assumption correct?\r\n\r\nI don't know. That behavior is determined by the WCF runtime, and I don't know it to that level of detail.\r\n\r\nIt's possible that the runtime is always creating a new copy of the `ExecutionContext` for every request that comes in. It's also possible that the runtime is (at least for synchronous requests) using a shared `ExecutionContext` for efficiency.","date":"2020-02-03T13:46:58.089Z"}